45:46.870 --> 45:48.786
but there's the circle
of life for you.

45:48.830 --> 45:51.622
Talk to you later.
Thanks for watching.

45:51.666 --> 45:53.124
♪ ♪

45:53.168 --> 45:54.208
(mouse clicks)

45:57.380 --> 46:00.256
♪ ♪

46:05.555 --> 46:07.680
(water dripping)

46:16.357 --> 46:18.399
Kristi:
Ever since she got that iPad,

46:18.443 --> 46:22.361
she liked to spend
a lot of private time
up in her room and...

46:22.405 --> 46:25.239
she watched a lot
of things that were...

46:27.619 --> 46:29.202
funny to her.

46:29.245 --> 46:31.787
Nothing that
was gross,

46:31.831 --> 46:36.042
or depressing,
and emotionally degrading...

46:37.629 --> 46:41.756
She liked--
that iPad just gave her a way

46:43.384 --> 46:46.469
kind of not to--
to socialize with the family.

46:47.472 --> 46:49.263
And I totally...

46:51.392 --> 46:52.808
regret the iPad.

46:54.229 --> 46:58.272
Anissa showed me
a picture once.

46:58.316 --> 46:59.941
She was in her bedroom,

46:59.984 --> 47:02.902
and I went up to see
what she was doing,
and I looked.

47:02.946 --> 47:05.905
<i>It was a picture</i>
<i>of this Slenderman character</i>

47:05.949 --> 47:07.406
<i>and Jack Skellington.</i>

47:07.450 --> 47:09.825
♪ ♪

47:09.869 --> 47:15.790
<i>At the time,</i>
<i>it doesn't seem to be anything</i>
<i>inherently dangerous.</i>

47:15.833 --> 47:19.460
I had no inklings
that I would need
to research this further.

47:20.672 --> 47:22.046
The iPads will be moving

47:22.090 --> 47:24.507
into elementary school levels
this year.

47:24.551 --> 47:28.803
So, at least,
our fifth-grade son is going
to be coming home with one.

47:30.306 --> 47:31.472
His own.

47:36.020 --> 47:40.982
Tom Haynes:
So this is the yearbook
from Anissa's fifth grade year.

47:43.069 --> 47:45.069
(chuckles)
And this is what Anissa wrote.

47:45.113 --> 47:47.780
it says, "You're like
a second dad to me."

47:48.866 --> 47:50.783
So that was really sweet.

47:50.827 --> 47:53.119
It's kind of tough
looking back on it,

47:53.162 --> 47:56.455
'cause if she felt that strong,
you know, just...

47:59.002 --> 48:00.376
maybe I could have done
something else.

48:05.967 --> 48:10.595
<i> Anissa was definitely</i>
<i> one of the biggest</i>
<i> outliers I've had</i>

48:10.638 --> 48:14.974
<i> just because she had</i>
<i> no solid connections</i>

48:15.018 --> 48:18.311
<i> with other</i>
<i> 4th and 5th-graders.</i>

48:18.354 --> 48:22.732
<i> Anissa would definitely cry</i>
<i> once every couple weeks,</i>
<i> I would want to say.</i>

48:22.775 --> 48:27.111
<i> Mostly about... kids</i>
<i> being mean to her at school.</i>

48:27.155 --> 48:31.115
<i> She wouldn't</i>
<i> be able to contain herself</i>
<i> in front of the whole class,</i>

48:31.159 --> 48:33.117
<i> and sometimes</i>
<i> she would just cry.</i>

48:33.161 --> 48:35.036
So other kids
were aware of her...

48:36.372 --> 48:39.123
emotions,
and being upset.

48:39.167 --> 48:41.959
And there's times
she would come in
from lunch/recess

48:42.003 --> 48:45.379
and cry about
not having friends.

48:47.425 --> 48:51.719
<i>I've guessed that Anissa made</i>
<i>a connection with Morgan</i>

48:51.763 --> 48:54.347
<i> and was happy</i>
<i> that they both were</i>
<i> into Slenderman,</i>

48:54.390 --> 48:56.307
<i> was happy that</i>
<i> she made a new friend,</i>

48:56.351 --> 48:58.309
<i> shared a connection,</i>
<i> shared interest,</i>

48:58.353 --> 49:02.229
and it may have spiraled
out of control from there.

49:02.273 --> 49:04.732
(classical score playing)

49:06.486 --> 49:09.904
(no discernible dialog)

49:27.173 --> 49:29.090
(mouse clicks)
(keyboard clacks)

49:30.593 --> 49:32.885
♪ ♪

49:35.056 --> 49:37.390
Abigail Baird:
<i> You couldn't set up</i>
<i> a better system to fail</i>

49:37.433 --> 49:39.558
In terms of "No one
at school likes you,

49:39.602 --> 49:41.602
"but here's this
open-ended monster

49:41.646 --> 49:43.229
who will embrace you."

49:44.565 --> 49:46.732
<i> The worst time</i>
<i> to be socially isolated</i>

49:46.776 --> 49:51.153
<i> is the time when</i>
<i> your brain and body</i>
<i> are begging for camaraderie,</i>

49:51.197 --> 49:54.031
<i> for kinship,</i>
<i> which is adolescence.</i>

49:54.075 --> 49:55.950
<i> It's the hardest time</i>
<i> to be alone.</i>

49:57.286 --> 49:59.495
<i> I think in the absence</i>
<i> of social contact,</i>

49:59.539 --> 50:02.164
<i> the Internet</i>
<i> can sometimes serve</i>

50:02.208 --> 50:05.084
<i> as a peer in a way,</i>
<i> or a peer group.</i>

50:06.796 --> 50:09.839
<i> Those two girls</i>
<i> in a tight-knit group</i>
<i> of eight friends,</i>

50:09.882 --> 50:11.549
<i> I don't think</i>
<i> this would've happened,</i>

50:11.592 --> 50:13.592
<i> because they wouldn't</i>
<i> have only been talking</i>
<i> to each other</i>

50:13.636 --> 50:15.261
<i> and they wouldn't</i>
<i> have been relying so heavily</i>

50:15.304 --> 50:17.096
<i> on information</i>
<i> from the Internet.</i>

50:20.017 --> 50:22.143
(engine starts)

50:36.033 --> 50:39.660
Kristi:
<i> Bill and I separated</i>
<i> in the summer of 2012.</i>

50:42.540 --> 50:45.791
<i> It was my decision.</i>
<i> I asked for a divorce.</i>

50:45.835 --> 50:47.960
<i> But when a situation</i>
<i> got really bad,</i>

50:48.004 --> 50:51.046
<i> he was willing to still</i>
<i> be there and stuff.</i>

51:05.688 --> 51:08.397
(turn signal clicking)

51:09.984 --> 51:11.984
<i> She's not allowed to see</i>
<i> her brother or sister.</i>

51:12.028 --> 51:16.155
<i> She's not allowed</i>
<i> to see any aunts or uncles,</i>
<i> or cousins or anything,</i>

51:16.199 --> 51:19.408
<i> so I wanted to have</i>
<i> as many people</i>

51:19.452 --> 51:21.869
<i> as she could have</i>
<i> as often as possible.</i>

51:27.251 --> 51:31.879
I try to bring her mentally
out of the environment

51:31.923 --> 51:36.175
and try to bring her
some sunshine in her day.

51:36.219 --> 51:39.053
But then when I leave,
I kind of feel...

51:42.058 --> 51:46.477
I feel happy
that I was able to see her

51:46.521 --> 51:51.357
and... make her smile
for a few minutes in a day.

51:51.400 --> 51:53.651
But on the other hand,
I'm still kind of sad

51:53.694 --> 51:57.404
that I'm leaving
without my daughter, and...

51:59.033 --> 52:03.994
The drive home is
sometimes heart-breaking...

52:04.038 --> 52:08.123
but... I know
that I'll be coming up

52:08.167 --> 52:09.834
and seeing her
in a couple days anyways,

52:09.877 --> 52:12.336
and I'll just repeat
the performance and--

52:12.380 --> 52:18.384
(sniffles)
and hopefully, someday,
this might be my last trip

52:18.427 --> 52:20.803
and-- and...

52:22.056 --> 52:24.473
And then
she'll be home for good.

52:24.517 --> 52:27.309
But that might be
a while off.

52:32.817 --> 52:35.150
(musical ringtone plays)

52:35.194 --> 52:38.237
Computer: You have
a prepaid call from...
Anissa: Anissa...

52:38.281 --> 52:41.490
Computer: An inmate at...
Man:
Washington County Jail.

52:41.534 --> 52:43.033
Computer:
This call will be recorded

52:43.077 --> 52:45.369
and subject
to monitoring
at any time.

52:45.413 --> 52:47.454
You may begin speaking now.

52:47.498 --> 52:48.789
(Anissa speaks)

52:48.833 --> 52:51.292
Hello, Anissa.
So, how was your day?

52:56.799 --> 52:57.923
Yeah?

52:59.218 --> 53:00.509
Define "pretty good."

53:13.441 --> 53:14.815
Do you know
who's sitting here?

53:16.569 --> 53:18.986
Yep, Tyler's sitting here.
Tyler: Hi!

53:20.197 --> 53:21.697
(Bill laughs)
How are you?

53:24.660 --> 53:26.160
I've been...

53:27.371 --> 53:29.330
pretty good
despite the cold.

53:30.333 --> 53:31.665
Hi, Ani!

53:33.586 --> 53:34.668
(laughs)

53:35.630 --> 53:36.670
What's up?

53:44.555 --> 53:46.639
Anissa! Anissa.

53:48.434 --> 53:50.100
We can all tell
you're a little spun up.

53:50.144 --> 53:52.186
Are you excited
to be talking to everybody?

53:53.606 --> 53:54.688
Yeah?

54:09.997 --> 54:12.539
Hey, hey hey! Anissa!
(laughter)

54:14.919 --> 54:16.669
Dial it back a notch.

54:16.712 --> 54:20.881
So, besides what
you've already like mentioned,

54:20.925 --> 54:22.383
what's up with you?

54:35.982 --> 54:37.064
Okay.

54:38.484 --> 54:40.442
Anissa: Yeah.
Just don't smile too much.

54:40.486 --> 54:41.652
Computer:
One minute remaining.

54:41.696 --> 54:43.278
All right,
we've got one minute,

54:43.322 --> 54:44.905
so you have a good night.

54:47.368 --> 54:49.326
Love you too.

54:49.370 --> 54:53.288
All right?
And I will see you tomorrow.

54:53.332 --> 54:56.792
So-- all right.
Computer: Thank you
for using IC solutions.

54:56.836 --> 54:58.043
Goodbye.
And there you have it.

54:59.046 --> 55:00.796
♪ ♪

